{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014E5ZFQCWPvtkHaeMr8ggrw","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→from datetime import datetime\n     2→from unittest.mock import create_autospec\n     3→\n     4→import pytest\n     5→\n     6→from services.core_service import CoreService\n     7→\n     8→\n     9→@pytest.fixture\n    10→def fixed_check_in():\n    11→    return datetime(2024, 1, 1, 12, 0, 0)\n    12→\n    13→\n    14→def test_create_record_returns_confirmed_status(fixed_check_in):\n    15→    service = CoreService()\n    16→    notifier = create_autospec(object, spec_set=True)\n    17→\n    18→    # Act\n    19→    result = service.create_record(\n    20→        display_name=\"Alice\",\n    21→        check_in=fixed_check_in,\n    22→        check_out=datetime(2024, 1, 3, 12, 0, 0),\n    23→    )\n    24→\n    25→    assert result[\"status\"] == \"confirmed\"\n    26→    assert notifier.mock_calls == []\n    27→\n    28→\n    29→def test_cancel_record_returns_cancelled_status():\n    30→    service = CoreService()\n    31→\n    32→    # Act\n    33→    result = service.cancel_record(record_id=\"abc-123\")\n    34→\n    35→    assert result[\"status\"] == \"cancelled\"\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7344ca3c-f9fb-4297-a42d-0eaa377642b4","uuid":"3c106f28-67c9-4b53-a8fa-98319a498244"}
